Four women have been rescued from an alleged human trafficking syndicate in Durban. (eNCA/Screenshot) DURBAN - Four women have been rescued from an alleged human trafficking syndicate in Durban. It is understood the women were lured by a potential job opportunity at a call centre and told they would be selling sim cards to high profile people. They travelled from Johannesburg to Durban earlier this week, and upon arrival, they discovered they were involved in the sex trade. Four women have been rescued from an alleged #humantrafficking syndicate in Durban. It is understood the women were lured by a potential job opportunity at a call centre and told they would be selling sim cards to high profile people. #DStv403 #eNCA pic.twitter.com/9h4ol1t2WZ  It is understood the women were kept in one room where one of the men would touch them inappropriately. One of the women managed to contact someone who alerted the police. A case of human trafficking is being investigated.